  "points": [
    {
      "title": "Subject pronouns (je, tu, il…)",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Say who you are talking about",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 1,
      "explanation": "The subject pronouns are je (I), tu (you, informal), il/elle (he/she), on (one/we, informal), nous (we), vous (you, formal or plural), ils/elles (they). Vous doubles as the polite singular — use it with strangers. On is how spoken French usually says 'we': on mange à midi.",
      "culture_note": "Choosing tu or vous is a real social decision. When unsure, start with vous and wait to be invited to tutoyer.",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: French personal pronouns",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_personal_pronouns"
        },
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: French grammar",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_grammar"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} suis de Paris.",
          "answer": "Je",
          "translation": "I am from Paris.",
          "hint": "I",
          "display_order": 1,
          "cell": "je"
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} es mon ami.",
          "answer": "Tu",
          "translation": "You are my friend.",
          "hint": "you — informal",
          "display_order": 2,
          "cell": "tu"
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} est ma sœur.",
          "answer": "Elle",
          "translation": "She is my sister.",
          "hint": "she",
          "display_order": 3,
          "cell": "elle"
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} sommes étudiants.",
          "answer": "Nous",
          "translation": "We are students.",
          "hint": "we",
          "display_order": 4,
          "cell": "nous"
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} sont d'Espagne.",
          "answer": "Ils",
          "translation": "They are from Spain.",
          "hint": "they (masculine)",
          "display_order": 5,
          "cell": "ils"
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} êtes très gentil.",
          "answer": "Vous",
          "translation": "You are very kind.",
          "hint": "you — formal",
          "display_order": 6,
          "cell": "vous"
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} travaille à Paris.",
          "answer": "Il",
          "translation": "He works in Paris.",
          "hint": "he",
          "cell": "il",
          "display_order": 7
        },
        {
          "sentence": "{{answer}} sont mes amies.",
          "answer": "Elles",
          "translation": "They are my friends (all women).",
          "hint": "they — all female",
          "cell": "elles",
          "display_order": 8
        }
      ],
      "paradigm": [
        "je",
        "tu",
        "il",
        "elle",
        "nous",
        "vous",
        "ils",
        "elles"
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Gender and number of nouns",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Name people and things, one or many",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 2,
      "explanation": "Every noun is masculine or feminine — learn each noun with its gender, because little about the word itself tells you. The plural usually adds a silent -s (livre → livres); since it isn't pronounced, the article carries the plural out loud. Endings give clues: -tion and -té are usually feminine, -age and -eau usually masculine.",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: French grammar — nouns",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_grammar"
        },
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: Grammatical gender",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grammatical_gender"
        }
      ],
      "drills": [
        {
