    {
      "title": "Present tense of -er verbs",
      "level": "A1",
      "function": "Talk about what people do",
      "source": "contributor",
      "reviewed": true,
      "display_order": 7,
      "explanation": "Ninety percent of French verbs end in -er and share one pattern. Drop -er, add: -e, -es, -e, -ons, -ez, -ent (parler → je parle, tu parles, il parle, nous parlons, vous parlez, ils parlent). Four of those six forms sound identical — the pronoun does the work in speech.",
      "culture_note": "",
      "references": [
        {
          "title": "Wikipedia: French conjugation — first group",
          "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_conjugation"
        },
        {
          "title": "Wiktionary: parler (French)",
          "url": "https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/parler#French"
        }
      ],
